{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8de98700-93ce-42be-b083-4c2cf262c03c","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## 1. File I/O During Evaluation (High Impact)\n**Line 13 in `EvalHeavy.csproj`:**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nProperty functions that perform file I/O execute during *evaluation*, not build. This blocks the evaluator with synchronous disk reads and cannot be cached across re-evaluations.\n\n## 2. Recursive Wildcard Glob (Medium Impact)\n**Line 9:**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" ... />\n```\nThe `**\\*.*` glob forces MSBuild to walk the entire directory tree during evaluation. This is expensive in large repos and invalidates the evaluation cache whenever any file changes.\n\n## 3. Deep Import Chain (Low–Medium Impact)\n```\ncsproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nThree levels of chained imports adds evaluation overhead. Each import requires a file open, parse, and merge pass. In isolation this is minor, but it compounds with the issues above since every re-evaluation must re-traverse the chain.\n\n---\n\n**Recommendations:**\n- Replace `File::ReadAllText` with a build target that reads the file at build-time, not evaluation-time.\n- Narrow the `**\\*.*` glob to specific extensions or directories.\n- Flatten the import chain or consolidate properties into fewer files.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"160adbd8-85ff-432e-9541-bc48b0778ece","outputTokens":358,"requestId":"DBC9:23ADA7:A0267AB:AF36F78:69FD39CF"},"id":"0c8e7aff-c4bc-46d8-86f2-de741eac54de","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:18:17.378Z","parentId":"ed607918-ba0f-4206-98e3-375c1a046a8c"}
